Medermycin (3) is a unique member of the pyranonaphthoquinone family of anti- biotics, isolated from Streptomyces sp. K73 (Takano et al. 1976). Biological evaluation of Medermycin showed that it is a C-glycoside antibiotic with potential therapeutic utility as an anticancer and antibacterial agent (Okabe et al. 1985; Tanaka et al. 1985). The group of medermycin analogues has been reported only about nine compounds so far (Takano et al. 1976; Okabe et al. 1986; Hayakawa et al. 1994; Lacret et al. 2018). Among them, it only Lactoquinomycin B which contains 5,14-epoxidation (Okabe et al. 1986). During our search for novel bioactive secondary metabolites from marine- derived Streptomyces (Zhou et al. 2018), the streptomyces strains SS17A, isolated from CONTACT Li Shen Zhoushan, People’s Republic of China (cid:1) 2019 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group ABSTRACT Lactoquinomycin C (1) and Lactoquinomycin D (2), two new medermycin derivatives together with six known compounds (3–8) were isolated from the rice solid fermentation of the marine-derived Streptomyces sp. SS17A. The intriguing structural features of the Lactoquinomycin D (2) which contains 5,14-epoxi- dation is relatively rare in medermycin derivatives. Compounds 1 and 2 exhibited no cytotoxicity against PC-3 and HCT-116 cancer cell lines, whereas compound 3 showed stronger cytotoxicity with IC50 values of 0.02 and 0.04 lM, respectively. A structure-activity relationship was observed for the cytotoxicity of the medermycin derivatives with a c-lactone unit is required for significant cytoto- xicity based on compounds 1–3. The 1H and 13C NMR data (Table S2) suggested a struc- tural similarity to anthraquinone-carbohydrate hybrids (Toshima et al. 2000) except for the C ring which was a characteristic 1, 2, 3, 5-tetrasubstituted aromatic ring at dH 7.49 (1H, d, J ¼ 2.5 Hz) and 7.09 (1H, d, J ¼ 2.5 Hz), an methyl group {dH 2.74 (3H, s, 4- Me)} and an hydroxyl group {dH 11.21 (1H, s, H-2-OH)}. The position of the methyl group at C-4 was confirmed by the HMBC correlations from 4-Me to C-3 (dC 124.7) and C-5 (dC 122.4). Finally, The position of the hydroxyl group was at C-2 which was further confirmed by the HMBC correlation from 2-OH to C-3 (dC 124.7). the ShengShan Island of Zhejiang Province, China, was selected for its cytotoxic activ- ity against the PC-3 human cancer cells (with an inhibitory rate of 100% for the EtOAc extract at a concentration of 20 lg/mL). Chemical investigations of the fermentation led to the isolation of two new medermycin derivatives Lactoquinomycin C (1) and Lactoquinomycin D (2), together with six known compounds (3–8). In this paper we describe the isolation, structure elucidation and biological evaluation of them. 2. Results and discussion The ethyl acetate extract from rice solid medium of Streptomyces sp.SS17A yielded eight compounds (1–8) (Figure 1). The new compounds (1–2) were determined by spectroscopic techniques (IR, UV, 1H and 13C NMR, 2D NMR, and MS), whereas the six known compounds were identified by their physical properties and spectroscopic data measurements, as well as by comparing the data obtained with published values, as being medermycin (3) (Okabe et al. 1985), aloesaponarin II (4) (Abdissa et al. 2017), laccaic acid D (5) (Gao et al. 2017), 3-methyl-antibiotic G-15F (6) (Nozomi et al. 1989), ascochlorin (7) (Satoshi et al. 1994) and LL-Z 1272d (8) (Satoshi et al. 1994). Compound 2 was also obtained as yellow solid with a molecular

carbons [dC 202.3, 189.6 and 169.4]. The 1D NMR data of compound 2 were very similar to those of Lactoquinomycin B (Okabe et al. 1986), except that the ring opening of the lactone moiety in Lactoquinomycin B. The structure was confirmed by 2D NMR spectra (Figure S1). Science, all natural medermycin derivatives known to date, the configuration of angolosamine and the A/B ring, which also has been confirmed by total synthesis (Tatsuta et al. 1990; 1991; Williamson et al. 2002), are absolutely conserved, it can be assumed that the configuration of 2 should be the same as medermycin. Thus, the structure of 2 was elucidated as shown, and was named Lactoquinomycin D. Compounds 1–3 were evaluated for cytotoxic activity assay against PC-3 and HCT- 116 cancer cell lines (Table S1). Compounds 1 and 2 exhibited no cytotoxicity against PC-3 and HCT-116 cancer cell lines, whereas compound 3 showed stronger cytotoxicity with IC50 values of 0.02 and 0.04 lM, respectively. A structure-activity relationship was observed for the cytotoxicity of the medermycin derivatives with a c-lactone unit is required for significant cytotoxicity based on compounds 1–3. 3. Experimental procedures 3.1. General experimental procedures

Optical rotations were obtained with a JASCO DIP-370 digital polarimetry (JASCO, Japan). IR spectra were recorded on a Bruker Tensor27 FT-IR spectrometer (Germany). UV was determined on METASH UV-8000s (Shanghai METASH Instruments Co. Ltd., China). 1H, 13C and 2D NMR spectrum were measured using Avance III 600 (1H 600 MHz; 13C 150 MHz, Bruker) spectrometers, which used TMS as internal standard and deuterated solvents is CD3OD or DMSO-d6. The high resolution mass spectrum was obtained using Agilent 6230 TOF LC/MS system mass spectrometer. Time-resolved fluorescence resonance energy transfer (TR- FRET) signals were measured by multifunc- tional microplate reader SpectraMax M5. Column chromatography was performed with silica gel (100–200, 300–400 mesh, Qingdao Haiyang Chemical Co., Qingdao, China) and Sephadex LH-20 (Uppsala, Sweden). The thin-layer chromatography (TLC) was car- ried out on silica gel plates (GF-254, Qingdao Haiyang Chemical Co., Qingdao, China) and the spots were visualized not only by UV light (k ¼ 254 nm) but also by spraying with developer, which contained 10% H2SO4 in ethanol. PC3 prostate cancer cell and human coloprectal cell were obtained from ATCC. 3.2. Actinomycic material

3.2.1. Collection, isolation and taxonomy Streptomyces sp.SS17A was isolated from marine sediments of Shengsi Island (Zhejiang province, China) by using standard dilution plating method. Strain was maintained in Gause’s solid medium consisting of (per liter) 20 g of soluble starch, 1 g of KNO3, 0.5 g of K2HPO4, 0.5 g of MgSO4(cid:2)7H2O, 0.5 g of NaCl, 0.01 g of FeSO4(cid:2)7H2O, 20 g of agar, 25 g of sea salt, pH = 7.2–7.4 and subcultured monthly. The strain SS17A was identified using 16S rDNA sequence analysis by TaKaRa (Dalian, China), and its DNA sequence using BLAST (nucleotide sequence comparison) was compared to the GenBank data- base. The 16S rDNA sequence of strain SS17A has been deposited in GenBank (accession number LC128344.1). A voucher strain (Streptomyces sp. SS17A) was preserved at the Laboratory of Institute of Marine Biology, Ocean College, Zhejiang University, China. 3.3. Extraction and isolation Colonies of the strain SS17A growing on Gause’s agar plate were inoculated into a 500 mL Erlenmeyer flask, containing 250 mL of Gause’s liquid medium, and then incubated at 28 (cid:3)C for 5 days on a rotary shaker (180 rpm) to produce seed broth. The seed broth (12 mL) was then transferred to a 500 mL Erlenmeyer flasks, each containing 40 g of steri- lized rice in 60 mL salt water (25 g sea salt per liter). After incubation in static cultivation for 2 months at 28 (cid:3)C. A total of 200 Erlenmeyer flasks were prepared for this study.

The whole fermented culture were extracted with ethyl acetate at room tempera- ture for a night three times. The resulting ethyl acetate part was dried vacuum, and the crude EtOAc extract (23.6 g) was separated by a column of silica gel eluted with CH2Cl2/MeOH (100:1 to 1:1) to obtain 13 fractions FrA-FrM after TLC analysis. Fraction FrK (1.68 g) was fractionated by Sephadex LH-20 (MeOH/CH2Cl2 ¼ 1:1) to give 7 fractions [Fr.K1-K7]. Fraction K3 (208.5 mg) was further separated by preparative HPLC applying a 10–100% MeOH (0.05% trifluoroacetic acid (TFA) was added into the solvent)/H2O for 30 min at a flow rate of 20 mL/min, to yielded compound 1 (4.1 mg, tR ¼ 11 min). Fraction K2 (267.8 mg) was further separated by preparative HPLC apply- ing a 10-100% MeOH (0.05% trifluoroacetic acid (TFA) was added into the solvent)/ H2O for 30 min, afforded compound 2 (2.4 mg, tR ¼ 10 min) and compound 3 (5.4 mg, tR ¼ 14 min). Fraction FrJ (1.21 g) was also fractionated by Sephadex LH-20 (MeOH/ CH2Cl2 ¼ 1:1) to give 6 fractions [Fr.J1-J6]. Fraction J3 (418.8 mg) was further separated by preparative HPLC applying a 10-100% MeOH (0.05% trifluoroacetic acid (TFA) was added into the solvent)/H2O for 30 min, to yielded compound 5 (5.1 mg, tR ¼ 9 min) and compound 6 (3.2 mg, tR ¼ 14 min).
